  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Money laundering criminal offenses)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Monetary transactions in criminally derived property)\n\n3. Regulatory Agencies Involved:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service\n\nThese statutes establish:\n- Reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Criminal penalties for money laundering\n- Requirements for suspicious activity reporting\n- Mechanisms for investigating and prosecuting money laundering activities\n\nPenalties can include significant fines and imprisonment, depending on the specific circumstances and severity of the offense.\n\nAdditionally, many states have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws.",
